Acquisition Functions - Comparison¶

Acquisition Functions (acq. functions) are used to find the best next possible point to sample when doing Bayesian Optimization. The term best in this context depends on what the user wants to achieve. In our case we want to find the most informative point so that our surrogate model (cf. Bayesian Optimization). In this notebook I will introduce three acq. functions. The first one is Expected Improvement (EI) which is commonly used and easy to implement. After that I will discuss Mutual Information (MI) and Upper Confidence Bound (UCB).

Comparison of Acq. Functions¶

The following code will illustrate the different choices resulting from each acq. functions introduced for the same sample.

In [9]:
# Set some parameters
k = gpflow.kernels.RBF(1, lengthscales=lengthscale)
N_samples = 5
sigma_n = 0.0
delta = 0.2 # Delta = ]0,1[
D = X.size # |D| = cardinality of a set: array.size in numpy
# print("|D|: " + str(D))

# Assume some initial samples
size_init = 2
np.random.seed(55)
index = np.random.choice(range(len(X)), size=size_init, replace=False)
X_sample_ei = X[index]
X_sample_ucb = X[index]
X_sample_mi = X[index]

Y_sample_ei = Y_true[index]
Y_sample_ucb = Y_true[index]
Y_sample_mi = Y_true[index]

# Compute EI
for i in range(N_samples):
    # Estimate model on samples
    m_ei = gpflow.models.GPR(X_sample_ei, Y_sample_ei, kern=k)
    m_ucb = gpflow.models.GPR(X_sample_ucb, Y_sample_ucb, kern=k)
    m_mi = gpflow.models.GPR(X_sample_mi, Y_sample_mi, kern=k)
    
    m_ei.likelihood.variance = sigma_n
    m_ei.compile()

    m_ucb.likelihood.variance = sigma_n
    m_ucb.compile()
    
    m_mi.likelihood.variance = sigma_n
    m_mi.compile()
    
    # Predict with model
    mean_ei, var_ei = m_ei.predict_y(X)
    mean_ucb, var_ucb = m_ucb.predict_y(X)
    mean_mi, var_mi = m_mi.predict_y(X)
    
    # Calculate EI
    ei = acq.get_EI(mean_ei, var_ei, np.max(Y_sample), zeta=0.0)
    # Calculate UCB
    beta_t = 2 * np.log( D * (i+1)**2 * np.pi **2 / 6 * delta )
    ucb = acq.get_ucb(mean_ucb, var_ucb, beta_t)
    # Calculate MI
    mi = acq.get_MI(X=X, Y_true=Y_true, locs=X_sample_mi, k=k, var_A=var_mi)
    
    # Plot
    utils.compare_acq([mean_ei,mean_ucb, mean_mi],[var_ei, var_ucb, var_mi], ['EI','UCB','MI'], X, Y_true, 
                      [X_sample_ei, X_sample_ucb, X_sample_mi], [Y_sample_ei, Y_sample_ucb, Y_sample_mi], ['x','o', 'D'],
                      size_init,False, True, [X, ei, 'EI'], [X, ucb, 'UCB'], [X, np.asarray(mi), 'MI'])
    
    # Append new point
    X_sample_ei = np.append(X_sample_ei, [X[np.argmax(ei)]], axis=0)
    Y_sample_ei = np.append(Y_sample_ei, [Y_true[np.argmax(ei)]], axis=0)
    X_sample_ucb = np.append(X_sample_ucb, [X[np.argmax(ucb)]], axis=0)
    Y_sample_ucb = np.append(Y_sample_ucb, [Y_true[np.argmax(ucb)]], axis=0)
    X_sample_mi = np.append(X_sample_mi, [X[np.argmax(np.asarray(mi))]], axis=0)
    Y_sample_mi = np.append(Y_sample_mi, [Y_true[np.argmax(np.asarray(mi))]], axis=0)
